The 2000 edition of <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Lost-New-York-Expanded-Updated/dp/0618054758/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;s=books&amp;qid=1229479226&amp;sr=1-1">Nathan Silver's <i>Lost New York</i></a> captions Abbott's picture as follows:

&quot;<i>HOUSES WITH PITCHED ROOFS.</i> 'A great number of excellent private dwellings are built of red painted brick, which gives them a peculiary neat and clean appearance,' a London visitor to New York wrote in 1819. The characteristic house was two or three stories high, sometimes twenty-five feet wide, two rooms deep, with a pitched roof and delicate dormers. These, built long before the Civil War, were at 512-514 Broome Street, and are now gone.&quot;

Perhaps they aren't gone, though. <a href="http://www.newyorkchanging.com/nychanging/512broome.html">Doulgas Levere's 1998 rephotograph of the same site</a> shows two small buildings in the same location, albeit with the dormers--and in 512's case, a whole story--removed. Google Maps shows yet another wrinkle: <a href="http://maps.google.com/maps?client=firefox-a&amp;rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&amp;channel=s&amp;hl=en&amp;q=&quot;512 broome street&quot;&amp;um=1&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;sa=N&amp;tab=wl">514 had a story <i>added</i> since 1998</a>.
